##Plot 1 - Boxplot: Economic Impact by Region

ggplot(climate_data, aes(x = Region, y = Economic_Impact_Million_USD, fill = Region)) +
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.7) +
  labs(title = "Economic Impact by Region",
       x = "Region",
       y = "Economic Impact (Million USD)") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 15) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 18, face = "bold"),
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
    legend.position = "none"
  )

This box-plot represents the distribution of economic impact (in millions of USD) for different regions. As you can see, each box represents the middle 50% of data points, and the line inside each box shows us the median economic impact. The whiskers extend to th e minimum and maximum values within the interquartile range, which represents the middle 50% of the data. Data points that go beyond are the outliers and these values are unusually high and this suggests significantly high economic impact. The outliers can point to unusual events that may not represent the typical performance of that region, which can lead to further study on why these values are so different from the rest.     axis.title = element_text(size = 14)

This plot shows us the two peaks of temperatures at around 15 degrees celsius and 30 degrees celsius. This can meaan the Northern region commonly experiences two main temperature ranges, which can correspond to the different seasons. ##Plot 1 Map

world_map <- map_data("world")
world_map <- na.omit(world_map)
world_map <- world_map %>%
  rename(Country = region)
climate_summary <- climate_data %>%
  group_by(Country) %>%
  summarise(
    Economic_Impact_Million_USD = mean(Economic_Impact_Million_USD, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

# Plot the map showing economic impact by region
world_map <-left_join(world_map,climate_data, by="Country")
## Warning in left_join(world_map, climate_data, by = "Country"): Detected an unexpected many-to-many relationship between `x` and `y`.
## ℹ Row 139 of `x` matches multiple rows in `y`.
## ℹ Row 7 of `y` matches multiple rows in `x`.
## ℹ If a many-to-many relationship is expected, set `relationship =
##   "many-to-many"` to silence this warning.
ggplot(world_map) +
  geom_polygon(aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group, fill = Economic_Impact_Million_USD), color = "white") +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "lightgreen", high = "darkgreen", name = "Economic Impact (Million USD)", na.value = "lightgrey") +
  labs(title = "Economic Impact by Region") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 15) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 18, face = "bold"),
    axis.title = element_blank(),  # Hide axis labels for simplicity
    axis.text = element_blank(),  # Hide axis text
    axis.ticks = element_blank()  # Hide axis ticks
  )
